[89.578896, "o", "                                                          \u001b[1;4mClick Library Onboarding Document\u001b[0m                                                           \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mWhat this repo actually does\u001b[0m                                                                                                                          \r\n\r\nClick is a Python library for creating command-line interfaces (CLIs). It provides a decorator-based approach to building CLI applications where you  \r\nannotate regular Python functions with decorators like \u001b[1;36;40m@click.command()\u001b[0m and \u001b[1;36;40m@click.option()\u001b[0m to automatically generate command-line parsers. The       \r\nlibrary handles argument parsing, type conversion, help text generation, and provides utilities for terminal output, file handling, and user          \r\ninteraction.                                                                                                                                          \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mHow to run it locally\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                 \r\n\r\nThis is a library, not an application, so you don't \"run\" it directly. To work with the codebase:                                                     \r\n\r\n\u001b[36m 1 \u001b[0mClone the repository                                                                                                                               \r\n\u001b[36m 2 \u001b[0mInstall in development mode: \u001b[1;36;40mpip install -e .\u001b[0m                                                                                                      \r\n\u001b[36m 3 \u001b[0mRun tests: \u001b[1;36;40mpython -m pytest tests/\u001b[0m                                                                                                                 \r\n\u001b[36m 4 \u001b[0mThe library uses a standard Python package structure with source code in \u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/\u001b[0m                                                                \r\n\r\nTo use Click in your own projects: \u001b[1;36;40mpip install click\u001b[0m and import with \u001b[1;36;40mimport click\u001b[0m.                                                                    \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mArchitecture: how the pieces connect\u001b[0m                                                                                                                  \r\n\r\nClick's architecture is built around several core concepts:                                                                                           \r\n\r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mCore Module (\u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40mcore.py\u001b[0m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m: Contains the fundamental classes like \u001b[1;36;40mContext\u001b[0m, \u001b[1;36;40mCommand\u001b[0m, \u001b[1;36;40mGroup\u001b[0m, and \u001b[1;36;40mParameter\u001b[0m that form the backbone of the CLI framework    \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mDecorators Module (\u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40mdecorators.py\u001b[0m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m: Provides the main user-facing decorators (\u001b[1;36;40m@command\u001b[0m, \u001b[1;36;40m@option\u001b[0m, \u001b[1;36;40m@argument\u001b[0m, \u001b[1;36;40m@group\u001b[0m) that transform regular functions\r\n\u001b[1m   \u001b[0minto CLI commands                                                                                                                                  \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mTypes System (\u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40mtypes.py\u001b[0m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m: Implements parameter type conversion and validation (strings, integers, files, paths, etc.)                               \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mOptions/Arguments (\u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40moptions.py\u001b[0m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m: Handles command-line option and argument parsing logic                                                             \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mContext System\u001b[0m: Uses a context stack to pass state between commands and subcommands, enabling nested command groups                                \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mTerminal Utilities (\u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40mtermui.py\u001b[0m\u001b[1m, \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40mutils.py\u001b[0m\u001b[1m)\u001b[0m: Provides utilities for terminal interaction, colored output, progress bars, and user prompts             \r\n\r\nThe flow works by: decorators register metadata в†’ core classes build command tree в†’ parser processes CLI input в†’ types convert/validate в†’ user        \r\nfunction executes.                "]
[89.579271, "o", "                                                                                                                    \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mCore files to read first (with one-line explanations)\u001b[0m                                                                                                 \r\n\r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/core.py\u001b[0m - Defines the fundamental Command, Group, Context, and Parameter classes                                                         \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/decorators.py\u001b[0m - Contains the main @click.command, @option, @argument decorators users interact with                                      \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/types.py\u001b[0m - Implements the type system for parameter conversion and validation                                                            \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/options.py\u001b[0m - Handles option and argument parsing logic                                                                                   \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/__init__.py\u001b[0m - Main module exports and public API surface                                                                                 \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40msrc/click/utils.py\u001b[0m - Utility functions for terminal operations and formatting                                                                      \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1;36;40mexamples/complex/complex/cli.py\u001b[0m - Real-world example showing advanced patterns like custom command groups                                          \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mKey patterns and conventions\u001b[0m                                                                                                                          \r\n\r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mDecorator Pattern\u001b[0m: Heavy use of decorators to annotate functions and build CLI structure declaratively                                             \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mContext Passing\u001b[0m: Uses \u001b[1;36;40mclick.Context\u001b[0m objects passed through a stack to share state between nested commands                                          \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mType Coercion\u001b[0m: Automatic type conversion based on parameter type annotations                                                                       \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mPass Decorators\u001b[0m: Pattern of \u001b[1;36;40m@click.pass_context\u001b[0m and custom pass decorators for dependency injection                                                \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mLazy Loading\u001b[0m: Commands can be loaded dynamically (see ComplexCLI example)                                                                          \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mChaining\u001b[0m: Commands can be chained together in groups                                                                                               \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mAuto-generated Help\u001b[0m: Help text is automatically generated from docstrings and parameter definitions                                                \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0m\u001b[1mEnvironment Variable Integration\u001b[0m: Automatic mapping of CLI options to environment variables                                                        \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mWhat is undocumented or surprising\u001b[0m                                                                                                                    \r\n\r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0mThe context stack mechanism is quite sophisticated but not immediately obvious from the surface API                                                \r\n"]
[89.579648, "o", "\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0mCustom command classes can override \u001b[1;36;40mlist_commands()\u001b[0m and \u001b[1;36;40mget_command()\u001b[0m for dynamic command loading                                                  \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0mThe \u001b[1;36;40mmake_pass_decorator\u001b[0m function allows creating custom dependency injection patterns                                                              \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0mError handling integrates deeply with the context system                                                                                           \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0mThe library has extensive terminal capability detection and cross-platform compatibility code                                                      \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0mType system is extensible - you can create custom parameter types by subclassing base types                                                        \r\n\u001b[1m вЂў \u001b[0mCommands can be invoked programmatically for testing via the \u001b[1;36;40mtesting\u001b[0m module                                                                        \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mWhere to go next\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                      \r\n\r\n\u001b[36m 1 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mStart Simple\u001b[0m: Begin with basic \u001b[1;36;40m@click.command()\u001b[0m and \u001b[1;36;40m@click.option()\u001b[0m examples                                                                       \r\n\u001b[36m 2 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mStudy Examples\u001b[0m: Look at the examples directory, especially \u001b[1;36;40mcomplex\u001b[0m for advanced patterns                                                           \r\n\u001b[36m 3 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mRead Tests\u001b[0m: The test suite in \u001b[1;36;40mtests/\u001b[0m shows comprehensive usage patterns                                                                            \r\n\u001b[36m 4 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mExplore Types\u001b[0m: Understand the type system in \u001b[1;36;40mtypes.py\u001b[0m for custom parameter handling                                                                \r\n\u001b[36m 5 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mContext Deep Dive\u001b[0m: Study how contexts work in \u001b[1;36;40mcore.py\u001b[0m for building complex nested CLI apps                                                         \r\n\u001b[36m 6 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mTerminal Features\u001b[0m: Explore \u001b[1;36;40mtermui.py\u001b[0m for progress bars, prompts, and colored output                                                                \r\n\u001b[36m 7 \u001b[0m\u001b[1mCustom Commands\u001b[0m: Learn to subclass \u001b[1;36;40mCommand\u001b[0m and \u001b[1;36;40mGroup\u001b[0m classes for specialized behavior                                                              \r\n\r\nThe library is designed to scale from simple single-command scripts to complex multi-command applications with subgroups, making it worth             \r\nunderstanding both the simple decorator API and the underlying class-based architecture.                                                              \r\n\r\n\u001b[4;35mREADME vs reality\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                     \r\n\r\n\u001b[3mNo README found in this repository.\u001b[0m                                                                                                                   \r\n"]
